statement_latex:
Let

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \left\{
 \begin{array}{lr}
   e^{-x} & \text{if}\quad x < t\\
   2(x+1) & \text{if} \quad x \geq t
  \end{array}
\right.
\end{align*}

Explain why there exists a number $t$ such that $f$ is continuous.

(Hint: apply the Intermediate Value Theorem to the function
$e^{-t}-2(t+1)$.)

statement_raw:
Let
:&lt;math>f(x) = \left\{
 \begin{array}{lr}
   e^{-x} &amp; \text{if}\quad x &lt; t\\
   2(x+1) &amp; \text{if} \quad x \geq t
  \end{array}
\right.&lt;/math>

Explain why there exists a number &lt;math>t&lt;/math> such that &lt;math>f&lt;/math> is continuous.

(Hint: apply the Intermediate Value Theorem to the function &lt;math>e^{-t}-2(t+1)&lt;/math>.)
